  "text": "The upstream connection pool overflow condition in Envoy is defined and handled across multiple C++ files in the envoyproxy/envoy repository:\n\n**Overflow State Definition:**\n\n1. **envoy/common/conn_pool.h** defines the `PoolFailureReason` enum (lines 96-105) with an `Overflow` state (line 98) that represents \"A resource overflowed and policy prevented a new connection from being created.\"\n\n**Primary Overflow Emission Points:**\n\n2. **source/common/upstream/conn_pool_map_impl.h** (lines 33-39): The `ConnPoolMap::getPool()` method checks if connection pool resources can be created. If `connPoolResource.canCreate()` returns false, it attempts to free an idle pool. If no pool can be freed, it increments `upstream_cx_pool_overflow_` stat and returns `absl::nullopt`, causing the pool creation to fail.\n\n3. **source/common/conn_pool/conn_pool_base.cc** contains three main overflow handling points:\n   - Line 138: Increments `upstream_cx_overflow_` when `canCreateConnection()` returns false during `tryCreateNewConnection()`\n   - Lines 175-180: Checks max requests limit in `attachStreamToClient()`, emits `upstream_rq_pending_overflow_` and fails with `PoolFailureReason::Overflow`\n   - Lines 282-288: Checks pending requests limit in `newStreamImpl()`, emits `upstream_rq_pending_overflow_` and fails with `PoolFailureReason::Overflow`\n\n**Resource Limiting Infrastructure:**\n\n4. **source/common/upstream/resource_manager_impl.h** implements `ResourceManagerImpl` which tracks four key resource limits:\n   - `connections_`: max concurrent connections per cluster\n   - `pending_requests_`: max queued requests\n   - `requests_`: max concurrent requests\n   - `connection_pools_`: max connection pool objects per host\n\n5. **source/common/common/basic_resource_impl.h** implements `BasicResourceLimitImpl::canCreate()` (line 29) which performs the actual overflow check: `return current_.load() < max()`\n\n6. **source/common/upstream/upstream_impl.h** (lines 206-211) implements `HostDescriptionImplBase::canCreateConnection()` which checks both per-host connection limits and cluster-wide connection resource limits via `cluster().resourceManager(priority).connections().canCreate()`\n\n**Callback Infrastructure:**\n\n7. **source/common/http/conn_pool_base.h** and **source/common/tcp/conn_pool.h** define callback interfaces (`onPoolFailure`) that are invoked when overflow occurs, allowing callers to handle the failure with the `PoolFailureReason::Overflow` reason.\n\n**Flow Chain:**\nWhen new streams arrive, `ConnPoolMap::getPool()` checks resource availability → `canCreateConnection()` validates host and cluster limits → `BasicResourceLimitImpl::canCreate()` checks if current < max → `tryCreateNewConnection()` either creates connection or emits overflow stat → `onPoolFailure()` callback invoked with `PoolFailureReason::Overflow`."
}

